## Ownership for Memory Safety


## Analogy
Kitchen counter: stack
Kitchen fridege: heap
Kitchen manager: compiler? executor?
Functions: cooking robots
foods: variables, data
tickets: pointer to the 
function call: robot A order hand over some food to robot B to process

A group of robots cooks in the kitchen.
They can put food on the counter.
They can also request a box in the fridge and keep a ticket referring to that on the counter.



## Kitchen space management
Only working robots can keep their stuff on the counter and the fridge.


In some office, there's no manager. So you need to order the robots to throw away food no longer needed as a programmer (C).
You may run into trouble if you order the robot to throw away your food while it will be used in the future.
In some office, there's a space manager. The manager throw away stale food.
There are two kinds of managers:
1. One that check the working schedule of the robots and throw away food as soon as it become useless (rust).
2. One that try to make space by looking up useless food in the fridging from time to time.

Only one robot can own the box in the fridge at one time. 
A robot may hand over the ownership to another robot.




